#Section IV. Gaussian Calculations

## 4.1: Optimizations (OPT)

### 4.1.1. Optimization of a Minimum

**Description**

One of the most important calculations in computational chemistry is the geometry optimization. This calculation searches for a minimum on the potential energy surface by searching for a place with a gradient of zero. There are a couple of different methods of finding a minimum, for example, steep or conjugate gradient (CG). While steep is guaranteed to find a minimum, it is much slower to converge than CG. Therefore, CG is the default for most programs.

It is important to note that the CG method searches for a point of (near) zero gradient, while trying to move in the direction of a minimum in all dimensions. As discussed in Section 3, we know that points of zero slope occur at both a maximum and a minimum, therefore always run a frequency to characterize the stationary point found with CG.

The initial geometry (input) for an optimization can greatly affect the output. One important example of this is symmetry. GAUSSIAN WILL NOT BREAK SYMMETRY. Therefore, unless you are looking for a symmetric structure (e.g., perfectly planar), either include the 'nosymm' keyword, or manually change angles/distances to break symmetry.

**Input**

Standard input with the following command line:

\# **opt** hf/3-21g

In GaussView, select 'optimization' from the 'Job Type' tab. Leave all other features set to the default.

**Output**

In the .log file, a single-point energy calculation is carried out at each step of the optimization. Following each step in the optimization the convergence criteria is printed.

Item Value Threshold Converged?

Maximum Force 0.041404 0.000450 NO

RMS Force 0.034777 0.000300 NO

Maximum Displacement 0.117104 0.001800 NO

RMS Displacement 0.124129 0.001200 NO

This information indicates that the calculation is not converged since none of the four criteria are satisfied (i.e., all indicate NO under Converged?). The calculation will continue until all four criteria are satisfied. At this point, the output will indicate that a "Stationary Point" has been found (which could either be a minimum or a transition structure) and prints the optimized bond lengths, angles and dihedral angles, as well as the Cartesian coordinates.

Item Value Threshold Converged?

Maximum Force 0.000164 0.000450 YES

RMS Force 0.000135 0.000300 YES

Maximum Displacement 0.000155 0.001800 YES

RMS Displacement 0.000164 0.001200 YES

Predicted change in Energy=-4.610148D-08

Optimization completed.

\-- Stationary point found.

\----------------------------

! Optimized Parameters !

! (Angstroms and Degrees) !

\-------------------------- --------------------------

! Name Definition Value Derivative Info. !

\--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

! R1 R(1,2) 0.9893 -DE/DX = 0.0002 !

! R2 R(1,3) 0.9893 -DE/DX = 0.0002 !

! A1 A(2,1,3) 100.0351 -DE/DX = 0.0 !

\--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

GradGradGradGradGradGradGradGradGradGradGradGradGradGradGradGradGradGrad

Input orientation:

\---------------------------------------------------------------------

\---------------------------------------------------------------------

When a .log file is opened in GaussView the geometry of the final structure is displayed. If you are interested in the different geometries sampled during the optimization, they can viewed by clicking the 'Read Intermediate Geometries' box at the bottom of the Open File window.

4.1.2. Optimization of a Transition State

**Description**

A transition state (TS) is a first-order saddle point, which means that it is a maximum in one direction and a minimum in all other directions (See Section 3). Optimizing a TS requires a special type of calculation. Note that finding a TS requires the use of chemical intuition to set up a good guess of the geometry. Generating these structures takes practice and patience, so don't worry if it doesn't work the first time. As with minima, always run a frequency calculation to make sure that the imaginary frequency corresponds to the reaction coordinate.

**Input**

Standard input with the following command line:

\# **opt=(ts,calcfc,noeigentest)** hf/3-21g

To speed up the calculation we also use the 'noeigentest' modifier. When multiple modifiers are added to a keyword surround them with brackets and separate them with a comma.

In GaussView the TS and calcfc modifiers can be selected from a dropdown menu on the 'Job Type' tab. To request 'calcfc' select calculate once from the second dropdown menu. The second modifier is added by typing 'opt=noeigentest' into the additional keywords section at the bottom of the Calculation window.

**Output**

The output for a TS is the same as for a minimum (Section 4.1.1).

4.1.3. Scanning a Coordinate

![](data:image/png;base64,)**Description**

There are times when we want to examine structures that are not stationary points. For example, we are often interested in plotting the energy of a system versus a dihedral angle. There are two different ways to go about this: 1) we can modify the angle and measure the energy; 2) we can modify the angle and relax the remainder of the dimensions before taking the energy. Both methods are referred to as a scan. It is generally preferable to constrain the coordinate and relax the remainder, but that is not always the case. If you do not need to relax the geometries, set up each point individually and run single-point energies. If you do need to relax the geometry, run a scan in Gaussian. The following example is for the rotation about the C-C bond of 1,2-dichloroethane, Figure 8.

Figure 8. Structure and atom numbering for 1,2-dichloroethane.

**Input**

Standard input with the following command line and additional input:

\# **opt=modredundant** hf/3-21g

Scan of the Cl-C-C-Cl dihedral of 1,2-dichloroethane in 10 degree

increments.

0 1

C -3.39805825 0.41262135 0.00000000

H -3.04140382 -0.59618865 0.00000000

H -4.46805825 0.41263454 0.00000000

C -2.88471603 1.13857763 1.25740497

H -1.81471603 1.13856430 1.25740471

H -3.24137067 2.14738755 1.25740510

Cl -2.81138143 1.24228567 -1.43703425

Cl -3.47139261 0.30891255 2.69443887

D 7 1 4 8 S 18 10.000000

The last line shows that the modredundant modifier is referring to a dihedral (D) defined by atoms 7, 1, 4 and 8. It is being scanned (S) in 18 steps of 10° increments.

This information can be added by hand in VI, or using the Redundant Coordinate Editor (Figure 9). If redundant coordinates have been defined, then 'Use Modified Redundant Coordinates' will automatically be selected in the calculation window.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Figure 9. Layout of the redundant coordinate editor in GaussView.

**Output**

GaussView will generate a PES plot that can be viewed by selecting Scan from the Results menu. The graph plots the dihedral angle (°) versus the energy (Hartree), Figure 10. Since the example molecule is symmetric, we only need to scan halfway around the bond to get the full picture of the possible minima. From this plot we see that the global minimum occurs at a ClCCCl angle of 180°, and there is a local minimum at 270°, which corresponds to a _gauche_ conformation. The energies are displayed in Hartees so it is difficult to obtain from this chart what the relative energy is between the two minima.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Figure 10. Scan output for the rotation of the C-C bond in dichloroethane viewed in GaussView.

In order to extract this information to make your own figures (especially if you need the plot to be in kJ mol<sup>-1</sup> rather than Hartrees) open the .log file in VI or in notepad. The energies are given in order in the summary paragraph at the bottom of the file. For example, if the energies from the above plot are converted to kJ mol<sup>-1</sup>, then it is simple to see that the difference in energy between the two minima is less than 10 kJ mol<sup>-1</sup> (Figure 11).

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Figure 11. Scan output for the rotation of the C-C bond in dichloroethane generated with an XY-scatter plot in Excel.

4.2: Frequency (FREQ)

4.2.1. Standard Frequency

**Description**

A frequency calculation is used to characterise a stationary point and determine the vibrational frequencies of a system. See Section 3.2 for a full description.

**Input**

Obtain your optimized coordinates by opening your optimization .log file in GaussView (make sure you are displaying the final optimization point!). By using GaussView to generate the frequency .com from the optimization .log, you ensure that the correct method and basis set are maintained. Remember, frequency calculations are always run at the same level of theory and basis set as the optimization. If not, the information obtained is useless!

Standard input with the following command line:

\# HF/3-21G **freq=noraman**

**Output**

The majority of the output is the same as before. The major points of interest for a frequency calculation are the calculated frequencies and the thermochemical data.

The frequency information typically looks as follows:

The first row of "Low frequencies" should be very small and close to zero. There will be 5 numbers for a linear molecule and 6 numbers for a non-linear molecule corresponding to the appropriate rotational and translational degrees of freedom. The next row of "Low frequencies" represent the lowest vibrational modes of the molecule, the smallest of which will be positive if a minimum is found or negative if a transition structure is found. The remainder should all be positive numbers in order to be of chemical interest! The mode to which these frequencies correspond are displayed in xyz coordinates under the appropriate vibration; however various programs, such as GaussView, can be used to visualize these vibrations.

This value must be multiplied by an appropriate scale factor (provided in Section 6) and then added to the total energy from the calculation in order to account for ground state motion of the molecule. Beware of units when doing these calculations!

To view the motion associated with this frequency, open the .log file in GaussView and select Vibration from the Result menu. Select the appropriate frequency and click Start Animation.

4.3: Single-Point Energy (SP)

4.3.1. Simple Single-Point Energy

**Description**

A single-point calculation is a calculation of an energy or property of a single structure on the potential energy surface. When there are no other keywords, an energy calculation is carried out. Since the geometry of a system is less dependent on basis set than the energy, we often use a lower level of theory to determine the geometry and a higher level of theory to obtain a more accurate energy to save time. In the literature, this is summarized as follows:

{Method/basis set for energy}//{method/basis set for optimization}

For example: MP2/6-311+G(2df,p)//B3LYP/6-31G(d) tells us that the optimization and frequency calculations were carried out with B3LYP/6-31G(d) and the energy calculations used MP2/6-311+G(2df,p). In addition to using a more accurate method/basis set combination, it is recommended that energy calculations use more rigorous convergence criteria, called SCF=tight. In G09 (the program we are using) this is the default.

**Input**

The 'SP' keyword can be used, but is not necessary. In the absence of any other commands, such as 'OPT', Gaussian will run a single-point energy.

\# mp2/6-311+g(2d,p) scf=tight

In GaussView, select 'Energy' from the 'Job Type' tab.

**Output**

In the .log file, the final energy is output near the end of the file, before the dipole moment information.

SCF Done: **E(RHF) = -74.9607025103** A.U. after 7 cycles

Convg = 0.2317D-09 -V/T = 2.0050

S\*\*2 = 0.0000

The method used to determine the energy is given on the SCF Done line. In most cases, the energy can also be obtained in the summary paragraph at the bottom of the file following 'HF='. The only exceptions to this are post-Hartree-Fock methods such as MP2 and CCSD, since in the course of finding these energies the HF energy is also determined.

In GaussView, the SCF Done energy is given in the Summary section of the Results menu.

**Relative Energies**

The raw energies that are obtained from single-point calculations are highly dependent on level of theory and the number of atoms/electrons in the system. Therefore, we generally report all energies _relative_ to a common system, often the global minimum. In the following equation, if molecule B is more stable than molecule A, then the relative energy will be positive. If molecule B is less stable than molecule A, then the relative energy will be negative.

Relative energies are generally very small when reported in Hartrees. To make these numbers more manageable (and to put them in terms more familiar to us), relative energies are reported in kJ mol<sup>-1</sup> (1 Hartree = 2625.5 kJ mol<sup>-1</sup>).

Due to how large a Hartee is, relative energies can be diagnostic of small calculation errors. The wrong basis set, method, charge or structure can change the energy of a system by hundreds of kJ mol<sup>-1</sup>, where this is much easier to see through relative energies. The following table provides normal ranges for different relative energies (note that these are absolute values). If you obtain a |relative energy| > 200 kJ mol<sup>-1</sup> for anything other than an acidity or basicity, then there is probably an error somewhere.

| Comparison | Equation | \|Range\| (kJ mol<sup>-1</sup>) |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Confomers |     | 0 - 80 |
| Reaction Energies |     | 0 - 100 |
| Barrier Heights |     | 0 - 150 |
| Acidity |     | 800 - 1400 |
| Binding Energy<br><br>(Ex. Hydrogen Bond) |     | 10 - 60 |

**GREP**

If you need to obtain the energy from a number of files, you can use the grep command in Linux. For example, for a series of single-point calculations, if you want the energy for the system in different files, you can type

grep "SCF Done" \*.log

The output will give you the name of the file and the energy found in that log file. You should note that this command will output all of the lines in the .log file where "SCF Done" was found (so an optimization would have more than one energy!). Also note that this line may appear in a single-point calculation that has failed to converge, so always check that the job finished normally.

The output for the grep command is conveniently listed alphabetically by file name, with each instance on its own line. The energies can be quickly entered into an Excel spreadsheet by copying the whole paragraph into Excel. Each line will be given its own cell. Select '**Text to Columns**' from the 'Data' tab in Excel. Follow the directions to convert the lines into individual cells. A quick way is to use the 'Delimited' option, then click 'Space' on the next window. Each word will be given its own cell, the first will be the file name, and somewhere in the middle will be the energy. The remaining columns can be deleted. Once you have gone through this process once, the next time you paste a line of text into Excel it will use the same method to convert it automatically to columns until you close the program.

4.3.2. Charges

**Description**

The partial charges assigned to each atom of a geometry can be determined in a variety of ways. Some of these methods include: Mulliken, Merz-Kollman and CHelpG. The default method is Mulliken, which simply cuts each bond in half and divides up the charge that way. While Mulliken charges can be used qualitatively, it is recommended that other methods be used when accuracy is important. Merz-Kollman and CHelpG both fit the partial atomic charges to an electrostatic potential (three-dimensional charge surface).

**Input**

Mulliken charges are automatically determined with all calculations. In order to request other forms, use the Population keyword and specify the atom type.

\# hf/6-31g(d) **pop=MK**

To request Merz-Kollman charges: MK; to request CHelpG charges: CHelpG.

**Output**

The charges allocated to each atom are provided at the end of output file. To view them in GaussView, select Charge Distribution from the Results menu. The default will be Mulliken, change the dropdown menu to ESP to view Merz-Kollman charges.

4.3.3. NMR

**Description**

The chemical shifts of a system are often utilized in experiment to monitor reactions and make sure the predicted product is being generated. One way that computational chemistry can help with experiment is to calculate the chemical shifts of all possible products and then see which spectrum matches experiment. This also allows for the easy identification of peaks. It is recommended that basis sets of at least triple-ζ quality with diffuse and polarization functions be utilized for high accuracy. However, the calculation of NMR signals requires the calculation of second derivatives (like a frequency calculation), and therefore, large basis sets may not be practical or even possible.

**Input**

Starting from an optimized geometry, use standard single-point input with the NMR keyword.

\# **nmr=giao** b3lyp/6-31g(d)

There are a couple of ways that you can calculate the peaks, GIAO (gauge-including atomic orbitals) is the most common. In GaussView, select NMR from the 'Job Type' tab, GIAO Method should be the default. To calculate J and K coupling constants use the 'spinspin' modifier.

**Output**

Here is some example output for a GIAO calculation.

XY= .0000 YY= 24.0670 ZY= .0000

If nmr=spinspin was input, the following information is additionally provided:

The first matrix (in lower triangle form) is for K coupling, which is isotope independent. The second matrix is for J coupling, and uses default isotopes unless others have been specified.

In GaussView, select NMR… from the Results menu to see a sample spectrum (without coupling).

4.3.4. Orbital Energies (Population)

**Description**

Another useful property of a molecule is the energy and shape of the molecular orbitals. In most cases we are only interested in the frontier orbitals (HOMO, LUMO etc.), they can often be used to predict major/minor products and relative rates.

**Input**

In Gaussian, an orbital calculation is called a 'population'.

%chk=_filename_.chk

\# **pop=regular** hf/6-31g(d)

In this example the modifier 'regular' has been added. This limits the output to the five highest occupied and 5 lowest virtual orbitals. In addition, a checkpoint file is required to view the orbitals.

**Output**

In the .log file, between the dipole information and the summary paragraph, the requested orbital energies are printed. For our example, the highest five occupied (O) and lowest five unoccupied (virtual, V) orbitals are shown, where column 1 is the orbital energy (ε, Hartrees).

Orbital energies and kinetic energies (alpha):

Before you can view the shape of the orbitals you need to convert the .chk file into a formatted checkpoint (.fchk). In your URACIL window, enter the following command:

formchk filename.chk

This will generate a new file with the same name and the .fchk extension. At this point you can delete the .chk file (it is fairly large). Transfer the .fchk to your Windows machine using the Binary function instead of the ASCII function.

When you open the .fchk in GaussView, 'Surfaces/Contours' will become available in the Results menu.

- Select New Cube from the Cube Actions menu. Make sure Molecular Orbital is selected in the top dropdown menu. Select the desired orbital, for example, HOMO. From the above data, we know that the HOMO is orbital 60. Click Ok.
- After a few seconds, the MO will show up in the top box. Select it, and then select New Surface from Surface Actions. This orbital should now be visible on the molecule.

4.3.5. Counterpoise Correction

**Description**

The Counterpoise correction developed by Boys and Bernardi is utilized to account for Basis Set Superposition Error (BSSE), which results from carrying out calculations not at the complete basis set limit. This is most commonly applied in situations where binding energy or interaction energy is being calculated. Since the binding energy is calculated as the energy of the dimer minus the energies of the monomers, BSSE results due to the dimer being treated with more basis functions than the individual monomers. In simple terms, this is like calculating the dimer energy with a triple-zeta basis set and the monomers with a double-zeta basis set. Counterpoise addresses this issue by calculating the monomer energies in the presence of the basis functions of the other monomer (e.g., B). However, the extra basis functions are for empty orbitals, therefore this method overestimates the BSSE, since some of these basis functions should be occupied by the electrons of B, and thus excluded from A by the Pauli exclusion principle.

The binding energy is normally defined as:

Where is the dimer energy, and and are the monomer energies (optimized separately).

The BSSE is calculated as the effect of introducing the basis functions of the other monomer without the atoms.

Boys, S. F.; Bernardi, F. _Mol. Phys._ **1970**, _19_, 553-566.

**Input**

The Counterpoise method requires additional input on the command line, as well as with each atom specification.

\# mp2/6-31g(d,p) **counterpoise=2**

water dimer hbond with counterpoise correction

0 1 0 1 0 1

O**(Fragment=1)** -2.02595866 -1.02310152 0.00000000

H(Fragment=1) -1.07901356 -0.86955269 -0.03630046

H(Fragment=1) -2.42893139 -0.39795922 0.60696795

O(Fragment=2) 0.76371048 -0.51433306 -0.23476488

H(Fragment=2) 1.40119573 -0.54347086 0.48242654

H(Fragment=2) 0.80173718 0.34420315 -0.66263114

First, in the command line, we add the keyword 'counterpoise=_N_', where _N_ is the number of fragments or molecules. Next, the charge and multiplicity must be defined for the dimer and each of the monomers in turn. Finally, you must define which atom belongs to which molecule or fragment.

In GaussView, the fragment can be defined in the Atom List Editor by viewing the Gaussian Fragment column. To select the counterpoise method in the Gaussian Calculation Setup window, select 'Use Counterpoise' from the General tab. You will still have to modify the charge and spin/multiplicity yourself with Notepad or VI if one of the molecules is charged.

**Output**

The corrected energy can be found in the .log file.

Counterpoise: corrected energy = -2660.083831739527

Counterpoise: BSSE energy = 0.003902746890

The first line is the corrected dimer energy (), and the second line is the BSSE in Hartrees.

4.4: Other Keywords

4.4.1. Isotopes

**Description**

A standard calculation uses the most abundant isotope for each atom. While this does not affect the number of electrons, it does affect the mass of the system, which is most easily observed in vibrational frequencies. For most calculations, the most abundant isotope is sufficient; however there are cases where you will want to use other isotopes. For example, <sup>13</sup>C or <sup>2</sup>H (D) labeled molecules for the determination of NMR chemical shifts.

**Input**

Alternate isotopes can be specified in any type of calculation. This information appears in the coordinates section of the .com file as part of the atom specification.

\# hf/3-21g

Single-point energy of CH2D2

0 1

C -1.06796116 0.36407766 0.00000000

H**(Iso=2)** -0.71130674 -0.64473234 0.00000000

H**(Iso=2)** -0.71128832 0.86847585 0.87365150

H -0.71128832 0.86847585 -0.87365150

H -2.13796116 0.36409085 0.00000000

In GaussView, the isotope can be defined in the Atom List Editor. Click the 'I' icon to view the 'Mass (Isotopologue 0)' column, Figure 13. Recognized isotopes are available as a dropdown menu.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Figure 13. Example of isotope specification using the atom list editor in GaussView.

**Output**

The output for the calculation will look the same as for default isotopes.

4.4.2. Solvation (SCRF)

**Description**

By default, Gaussian calculations are carried out in the gas phase (a vacuum). However, most chemistry of interest occurs in a solvent of some kind, for example, water. One way to account for environmental effects is to place the solute in a bulk solvent that is described primarily by the dielectric constant of the medium. This methodology is called implicit solvent, since there are no contacts explicitly included. For example, hydrogen bonding to the solute is not included.

![](data:image/tiff;base64,)

Figure 14. Description of how the solvent accessible surface is formed with self-consistent reaction field (SCRF) methods.

In general terms, the SCRF method of implicit solvent places a sphere around each atom in the solute that includes the atomic volume (related to the van der Waals radius) (Figure 14). This surface (once smoothed) represents the Solvent Excluded Surface (SES). Next, a solvent probe (assumed to be a sphere) is rolled along the surface to form the Solvent Accessible Surface (SAS), which represents how close a solvent molecule can possible get to the solute. The SAS is then smoothed so that the resulting surface is mathematically well behaved. Next, the SAS is divided into triangular pieces called 'tesserae', which are small enough to be flat. The response of the surrounding environment to the solute (based on dielectric) is then represented by a point charge at the center of each of the tesserae. This treatment requires two pieces of information to define the solvent: the probe radius and dielectric constant. These constants are programmed for a variety of solvents.

For a more in-depth discussion of SCRF methods see:

- Cramer, C. J. Chapter 11 of _Essentials of Computational Chemistry: Theories and Models_; Wiley: Chichester, West Sussex, England, 2004;
- Tomasi, J.; Mennucci, B.; Cammi, R. _Chem. Rev. (Washington, DC, U. S.)_ **2005**, _105_, 2999-3093.

**Input**

Solvation can be added to most types of calculations (e.g., optimizations, frequencies, energies). The keyword to use is SCRF for self-consistent reaction field.

\# HF/6-31G **SCRF=(IEFPCM,solvent=water)**

The specific equations used to treat the solvent medium vary with method, the default is called IEFPCM. Some other options include CPCM and SMD. The second modifier gives the medium, in this example water, where there are many solvents available to choose from. The method and solvent can be selected from dropdown menus in the 'Solvation' tab of the Gaussian calculation window.

The effect of solvent is broken up into two components, the electrostatic and non-electrostatic terms. For most calculations the non-electrostatic term is small, however, in the case of Gibbs energy it can be important and therefore the SMD method is recommended.

**Output**

The output will look the same as for a gas-phase calculation with the exception of some additional lines in the .log file regarding the method selected, dielectric constant, radius of the solvent and SCRF contribution to the energy.

4.4.3. Intrinsic Reaction Coordinate (IRC)

**Description**

When studying reactions, it is important to make sure that the transition state that is optimized actually connects the reactants and products. For simple reactions, such as unimolecular rearrangements, inspection of the mode corresponding to the imaginary frequency is enough. However, for more complex systems it is common practice to run an IRC calculation. The IRC reads in the frequency information then runs optimizations along the coordinate that is a maximum to get to the reactant and product.

**Input**

An IRC calculation requires frequency information, since you have to run one to determine that you have found a TS, we can save some time by saving a .chk file and using it as input for the IRC. Copy your .chk so that you have two more copies with -ircf and -ircr endings.

For example:

cp dA-hydrolysis-TS-f.chk dA-hydrolysis-ircf.chk

In GaussView:

- Select IRC from the 'Job Type' tab.
- Change the first dropdown menu to 'Forward only' (or 'Reverse only' for the other direction).
- Change the Force Constants dropdown to 'Read from .CHK'
- Click the 'Compute more points' box and change the number to 20. This is how many optimization steps it should take before stopping.
- In the 'Link 0' tab, change the 'Chkpoint File' dropdown menu to Specify and write the name of the .chk file you made in here.

\# b3lyp/6-31g(d) **irc=(forward,maxpoints=20,rcfc)**

Since we want to follow the coordinate to the reactant and product you need two calculations, one forward and one reverse. Note that a forward IRC may not necessarily lead to a product.

**Output**

The IRC calculation will run until it finds the minimum or runs out of steps. In either case, you will have to submit the final point for a geometry optimization, so it is okay if it didn't reach the minimum.

In GaussView, open one of the IRC .log files. IRC/Path will be available in the Results menu. This will show a PES (Figure 15) with the TS that you started from at the top. Clicking on the lowest energy point will change the displayed geometry, which can be used to setup an optimization.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Figure 15. Example IRC output viewed using GaussView.

4.4.4. ONIOM

**Description**

The ONIOM method (Our own N-layered molecular Orbital Method) is a hybrid technique that allows different parts (layers) of the system to be treated with different levels of theory. ONIOM can be used for optimizations, frequencies, and energy calculations, so long as all the methods being used are available for the calculation. The basic idea behind ONIOM is to treat the chemically important section of a system with a high-level, accurate method, while the remainder of the system is treated with a fast, low-level method. The ONIOM energy of the system can be thought of as the energy of the whole system (referred to as the real system) treated with a low-level method, combined with a correction for moving from the low- to high-level method in the smaller (model) region. A parallel equation can be developed for a three-layer model, called ONIOM3.

Figure 16. Schematic for an ONIOM extrapolation calculation.

_(1)_

In ONIOM terminology the 'real' system is the entire molecule/complex (all atoms), the 'model' system is the important atoms that need more accuracy, 'high' indicates that the system is treated at the high level of theory and 'low' indicates treatment with a lower level of theory. For example, one can use B3LYP/6-311+G(2df,p) as the high-level method and PM3 as the low-level method. This is summarized as ONIOM(B3LYP/6-311+G(2df,p):PM3), which follows the form: ONIOM(High:Low).

In this first problem, we will investigate how to select method combinations. First, consider the size of the system, and what method/basis set combinations can be used based on your available resources. Next, consider what kind of calculation you want to run. Finally, consider the types of interactions present in the system and make sure that they are being treated properly with at least one method.

How do you know that your method selection is correct? Since the goal is to avoid running the high accuracy method on the full system, it is difficult to be sure that you have selected the correct methods. To address this issue, Morokuma and Vreven developed the S-value test. The error in the relative energy obtained with an ONIOM calculation is the difference between the relative energy determined with the high-level method on the real system and the ONIOM combination _(2)_.![](data:image/png;base64,)

_(2)_

Next introduce the definition of an ONIOM energy, i.e., substitute _(1)_ into _(2)_:

_(3)_

Which rearranges to:

_(4)_

The difference in energies determined with Real and Model systems at the same level of theory is referred to as the "substituent effect". If the ΔS values for the Low and High methods are the same, then the ONIOM method exactly reproduces the target method. When selecting High:Low method combinations then, you are trying to find a low level method with a substituent effect similar to the high level. Basically, this means that you want methods that treat the system similarly. Therefore, _ab initio_ methods generally pair well (MP2 with HF) and _ab initio_ and DFT methods pair poorly. Since the S-value test requires a high-level calculation on the full system, the S-value is generally determined on a smaller, representative system, and then applied to the target system.

In addition to selecting the methods that you are going to use to treat the system, ONIOM calculations also require you to define what atoms belong in the high and low-level regions. There are a few things that you need to keep in mind when dividing the model:

- What interactions/features in your system cannot be treated at the low level?
- Is a bond being cut in half? Recall that the high-level calculation is carried out on a 'model' system. To generate the model, any place where a bond is being cut in half, resulting in a 'dangling bond', a hydrogen atom is introduced with a bond length that is linearly related to the bond it is replacing. As a rule, avoid cuts that result in H<sub>2</sub>.
- If a bond is being cut, does this break any delocalization? As a general rule, you should avoid cutting an aromatic ring in half. The best cuts are between two sp<sup>3</sup> hybridized carbon centers.
- Nothing can move between layers. For example, the charge of the model region stays constant, which can affect any noncovalent interactions that occur across the boundary.

The math involved for frequency calculations is more involved, and the interested reader is referred to the development articles by Vreven and Morokuma.

- Humbel, S.; Sieber, S.; Morokuma, K. _J. Chem. Phys._ **1996**, _105_, 1959-1967
- Dapprich, S.; Komaromi, I.; Byun, K. S.; Morokuma, K.; Frisch, M. J. _THEOCHEM_ **1999**, _462_, 1-21.
- Vreven, T.; Morokuma, K. _J. Comput. Chem._ **2000**, _21_, 1419-1432.

**Input**

![](data:image/png;base64,)Specifying ONIOM requires keywords on the command line, and information on each line of the atomic coordinates. The input for this type of calculation is fairly complicated, so it is recommend that you use GuassView to set up your .com files.

Figure 17. Hydrogen-bonding dimer.

The following stepwise instructions are for a hydrogen-bonding dimer for C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>5</sub>CO<sub>2</sub>H (Figure 17). If we use our chemical intuition, we can be fairly sure that the strength of the hydrogen bond likely does not require the treatment of the phenyl rings with a high accuracy method such as CCSD(T). Therefore, we can probably treat the phenyl rings with something like MP2.

It is important to be careful to only cut along sp<sup>3</sup> hybridized bonds. This is because the calculations on the 'model' region add a hydrogen atom at the dangling bond positions. In this example, the model calculations are carried out on a formic acid dimer.

Step 1: Define the Model Region

In GaussView, select 'Select Layer' from the 'Edit' menu. A new window will open. Initially, all atoms will be defined as 'High'. Make sure the menu is set to 'Low' then select the atoms that you want to treat with the low-level method (hold shift to select more than one atom at a time). Once you have selected the atoms, click 'Apply' then 'Close'. Note that if you simply use the X button to close the window none of your changes will be implemented. Under the default display options, atoms in the high-level region will be in ball and stick format, while the low-level atoms will be in wireframe (Figure 18).

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Figure 18. Appearance of a hydrogen-bonding dimer, where the less important phenyl rings are in the low layer.

Step 2: Define Link Atoms

Because the calculation requires that the phenyl ring be replaced by a hydrogen atom during the model calculations, we need to tell the program what atoms are chemically bonded to the high-level atoms. GaussView will try to do this itself, but it is not always right. Open the Atom List Editor and click the 'L' icon to view the ONIOM input (L is for layers). The columns that we are interested in are 'Layer' and 'Link #' you can ignore all the other ones for now. We want to make sure that atom 3 is linked to 12 and 18 to 27 (Figure 19).

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Figure 19. ONIOM specific columns in the atom list editor of GaussView.

Step 3: Define Methods

In the Calculation window, go to the Method tab. In the top right corner of the tab is a box for ONIOM. When this box is selected, additional tabs become available for High, Medium, and Low layers. If no atoms have been defined as Medium, this tab will be inactive and grayed out. Each layer requires the same information as for a standard calculation. In this case, both the Real and Model systems have a charge of zero and are singlets. Changes to these tabs will modify the Keyword command line shown at the top of the window. For example, the High layer can be treated with CCSD(T)/aug-cc-pVTZ and the low layer with MP2/aug-cc-pVDZ.

Here is a portion of the .com file.

\# oniom(ccsd(t)/aug-cc-pvtz:mp2/aug-cc-pvdz)

H -1.18639996 -0.10299845 0.00131500 L

H -1.18582396 4.21791755 -0.00125800 L

H -3.68097096 4.21797755 -0.00263100 L

Let's go through some of the differences between this and standard input.

_Command Line_: In the place of the method/basis set, we now have the ONIOM specification where the methods are separated by a colon. ONIOM(High/High basis:Low/Low basis).

_Charge Spin/Multiplicity_: Gaussian requires the charge and spin/multiplicity for each of the three calculations. \[Low real\] \[Low model\] \[High model\]. The last two sets should be the same.

_Atom Specification_: For each line, after the X,Y,Z coordinates, is the layer specification (L, M or H) followed by and link atom information. In this example, carbon atom 3 is linked to atom 12 and in the model system this carbon is replaced by a hydrogen atom.

**Output**

The output for an ONIOM calculation is like three calculations in one and can be very complicated, so you will want to use GaussView to view your results. Single-point energies are simple enough for you to see the results in the .log file. Once the energy has been determined for each of the three calculations, the total is printed. Here is an example for an ONIOM(MPWB1K/6-31G(d):PM3) calculation.

ONIOM: calculating energy.

ONIOM: gridpoint 1 method: low system: model energy: 47.847577060403

ONIOM: gridpoint 2 method: high system: model energy: -3031.802602202319

ONIOM: gridpoint 3 method: low system: real energy: 245.292490597727

ONIOM: extrapolated energy = -2834.357688664994

The ONIOM extrapolated energy is the value you report. Note that the 'HF=' energy reported in the end paragraph that you may have used for other calculations is NOT the ONIOM energy, and is in fact .
